🚀 EC2 Instance Setup Documentation (Ubuntu)
📌 Overview

This document describes the setup of an AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance, including creation, SSH access, and initial system updates.

🧱 1. EC2 Instance Creation (AWS Console / ClickOps)

The instance was created using the AWS Management Console (ClickOps method):

Configuration:
AMI (Operating System): Ubuntu Server (LTS version)
Instance Type: (e.g. t2.micro / t3.micro)
Key Pair: Existing/new .pem key pair generated via AWS
Network Settings:
SSH (port 22) enabled in Security Group
Storage: Default EBS volume (gp2/gp3 depending on selection)
Result:

A running EC2 instance with a public IPv4 address was provisioned.

🔐 2. SSH Access Setup

The instance was accessed via SSH using a PEM key pair.

Command used:
ssh -i path/to/key.pem ubuntu@<EC2-PUBLIC-IP>
Notes:
Default login user for Ubuntu EC2 instances is ubuntu
The .pem file must have restricted permissions:
chmod 400 key.pem
🖥️ 3. Initial Login

After successful authentication:

Connection established to EC2 instance via SSH
User confirmed as:
whoami
# ubuntu
🔄 4. System Update & Upgrade

The system packages were updated to ensure security patches and latest package versions were installed.

Commands executed:
sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y
Purpose:
apt update → refresh package index from repositories
apt upgrade → install latest versions of installed packages
Outcome:
System packages were upgraded to latest stable versions
Security patches applied
Base system brought up to date
🧠 Key Notes / Learnings
EC2 Ubuntu instances do not require root login by default
Administrative tasks are performed using sudo
SSH access is controlled via key pairs, not passwords
Security Groups act as the primary firewall for inbound traffic
Updating packages is a standard first step after provisioning any server

